feat: Add tool support to ollama-bash-lib

This change introduces tool support to the `ollama-bash-lib`, allowing users to define and use tools with Ollama models.

New functions:
- `ollama_tools_add`: Adds a tool with a name, command, and JSON definition.
- `ollama_tools`: Lists all registered tools.
- `ollama_tools_count`: Returns the number of registered tools.
- `ollama_tools_clear`: Removes all registered tools.
- `ollama_tools_is_call`: Checks if a model's response contains a tool call.
- `ollama_tools_run`: Executes a tool by name, passing arguments as a JSON string.

Updates:
- `_ollama_payload_generate` and `ollama_chat_json` now include tool definitions in API requests.
- `ollama_messages_add` now supports the "tool" role for adding tool results to the message history.
- All changes are compatible with Bash v3.2.

Two new demo scripts are included:
- `demos/ollama_tools_simple.sh`: Demonstrates a tool with no arguments.
- `demos/ollama_tools_with_args.sh`: Demonstrates a tool that takes arguments.

pull_request.body: ## What's Added A clean, professional analytics dashboard that gives developers real-time visibility into agent performance - something the framework was missing. ## Why This Matters Eremos agents run in the background detecting blockchain signals, but there was no way to see how they're performing. This dashboard solves that by automatically tracking and visualizing: - Agent signal counts and confidence scores - Recent detection activity - Signal type distribution ## Key Features - **Zero config** - Works immediately with existing agents - **Real-time updates** - Live monitoring of agent activity - **Clean UI** - Professional dark theme, no bloat - **Responsive design** - Works on desktop and mobile ## Technical Implementation - Lightweight analytics engine that captures signals automatically - Simple HTTP server for the dashboard interface - Clean integration with existing logger system - Production-ready with proper error handling ## Usage ```bash npm run dashboard # Visit http://localhost:3001 ``` Makes Eremos much more developer-friendly by providing visibility into the swarm's performance.

pull_request.body:
<!--
Thanks for contributing to Valkey GLIDE!

Please make sure you are aware of our contributing guidelines [available
here](https://github.com/valkey-io/valkey-glide/blob/main/CONTRIBUTING.md)

-->

Implement a framework for retrieving the protobuf ConnectionRequest message
that the PHP ValkeyGlide and ValkeyGlideCluster constructors generate.

Add tests to validate various command inputs by examining the message
deserialized into PHP protobuf classes.

Fix various bugs:
- When using multiple addresses only the first address was used.
- Reconnection strategy was not being used.
- Client AZ was not being used.
- Connection timeout was not being used.
- Disabling periodic checks did not disable it correctly.
- Made defaults for connection timeout and reconnection strategy consistent with Rust client.

Integrate tests into CI:
- Register the test class
- Install PHP dependencies through composer in CI
- Generate PHP protobuf objects in CI
- Add dependency on symfony-polyfill to resolve issues finding ctype_* functions

comment.body:
Never heard of this one, an arch triple is commonly spelled ARCH-OS-LIBC, but distros more often than not provide `libsqlite3.so`, so that the provider package `SQLitePCLRaw.provider.sqlite3` is supposed to "just work". [Explicitly register it](https://github.com/ericsink/SQLitePCL.raw/blob/main/README.md#a-trio-of-packages) on startup. Beware only of `SOVERSION`ed library filenames, like how Debian does more and more often:

```
$ ls -noh /lib/x86_64-linux-gnu/libsqlite3.*
lrwxrwxrwx 1 0   19 2025-07-25 19:04:34 /lib/x86_64-linux-gnu/libsqlite3.so.0 -> libsqlite3.so.0.8.6
-rw-r--r-- 1 0 1.5M 2025-07-25 19:04:34 /lib/x86_64-linux-gnu/libsqlite3.so.0.8.6
```

The second expected symlink, `libsqlite3.so -> libsqlite3.so.0`, is conspicuously missing. If that's the case in your distro, just add it in the same directory and run `sudo ldconfig` so that it caches the path to the SO for the loader.

@ericsink, to answer your question, you likely have Windows, and if you have Windows, then you have WSL2, a lightweight but very real VM with the Linux kernel. VSCode and VS2022 both can build and debug inside it directly with appropriate extensions installed:

```
C:\>wsl
~$ uname -mrsv
Linux 6.6.87.2-microsoft-standard-WSL2 #1 SMP PREEMPT_DYNAMIC Thu Jun  5 18:30:46 UTC 2025 x86_64
```
